    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1844-01-23_page01.jpg"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#North-Audley-Street-1_ENK">1)     1 North Audley</placeName>
                        <date when="1844-01-23">Jan 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> 44</date></dateline>
                    <salute>
                        Dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName><lb/>
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p> 
                  
                    <note>93</note>
                    
                    With respect to my rose<lb/>
                    trellis -- there is no rose<lb/>
                    without thorns ! --<lb/>
                    Il n'y a ici qu'une petite<lb/> 
                    difficulle - manque de<lb/>
                    fonds --<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    If you can afford to advance<lb/>
                    three pounds for me till<lb/>
                    I return home well &amp; good<lb/>
                    I shall be glad to have the<lb/>
                    new wire and new post<lb/>
                    trellis - and moreover<lb/>
                    I shall be obliged to you ma'am<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    But if you cannot <choice> 
                    <orig>with-<lb/>
                    out</orig>
                    <reg>without</reg>
                    </choice>
                    inconvenience do this<lb/>
                    I would rather let the <choice> 
                    <orig>con-<lb/>
                    cern</orig>
                    <reg>concern</reg>
                    </choice>
                    <hi rend="underline">wholly</hi> or brokenly quite<lb/>
                    alone till I return, when in<lb/>
                    the course of time &amp; <unclear> sucking my<lb/>
                    paws</unclear> at economic home I shall<lb/>
                    be able to pay for <hi rend="underline">all</hi> - <choice> 
                    <orig>includ<lb/>
                    ing</orig>
                    <reg>including</reg>
                    </choice>
                    L50 which I have borrowed<lb/>
                    &amp; must pay in May to the good<lb/>
                    <unclear></unclear><lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1844-01-23_page02.jpg"/>
                    2)
                    Every guinea shilling or<lb/>
                    penny that I can rap or<lb/>
                    run I shall want to get<lb/>
                    me over Easter, whether<lb/>
                   in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> most expensive<lb/>
                    or on the road almost<lb/>
                    equally expensive visiting<lb/>
                    friends &amp; bails to servants<lb/>
                    vous comprenez <unclear></unclear> or in<lb/>
                    M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> . -'s phrase " Do I make <choice> 
                    <orig>my=<lb/>
                    self</orig>
                    <reg>myself</reg>
                    </choice>
                    understood "<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I know you will at<lb/>
                    this moment or perhaps<lb/>
                    before this moment say to<lb/>
                    yourself that on or about<lb/>
                    Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> . 9 - or 10t<hi rend="superscript">h</hi> . <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> will<lb/>
                    have Quarter Ann<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> . (due Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> -) £85,,10,,0<lb/>
                    <add>out of</add> which surely she can afford<lb/>
                    this poor little £3 for her rose trellis<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    But dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">madam</persName> please<lb/>
                    comprehend that the above named<lb/>
                    £85,,10 - plus £21,,10- must go to<lb/>
                    your Ladyship for House acct<lb/>
                    On the first of March next - And<lb/>
                    if I touch or devour any part of it<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1844-01-23_page03.jpg"/>
                    (3
                    now I cannot replace it then<lb/>
                    without pinching difficulty<lb/>
                    to my clearing out of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> -<lb/> </p> <note>94</note>
                    <p>
                    I hate pinching difficulties &amp;<lb/>
                    always avoid them to the best of<lb/>
                    my capacity &amp; discretion<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    Nota bene I am indulging<lb/>
                    myself in setting up 35 West Indian<lb/>
                    beautiful birds (just received<lb/>
                    from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarmA1" cert="medium">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Carmichael</persName>) and which<lb/>
                    I have destined for a recess in<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fannys</persName> drawing room where they<lb/>
                    will look beautiful &amp; she likes the<lb/>
                    thought - The mere setting up will<lb/>
                    cost £5 - the glass and frame<lb/>
                    work habitation for the beauties<lb/>
                    will come to about £5.10 -<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> insists upon paying for<lb/>
                    the house - I for the birds -<lb/>
                    " Each pleasure has its price " &amp;c<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    <del>I have had</del> My old <choice> 
                    <orig>embroider<lb/>
                    ed</orig>
                    <reg>embroidered</reg>
                    </choice>
                    skreens or rather my dear<lb/>
                    mother <hi rend="underline">your</hi> old embroidered<lb/>
                    skreens which I gave you &amp; took<lb/>
                    back from you <unclear></unclear> gold ring<lb/> 
                    fashion I have had elegantly<lb/>
                    mounted by Law, with gilt<lb/>
                    framer &amp; plate glass and<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1844-01-23_page04.jpg"/>
                    <unclear></unclear><lb/>
                    We go to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RaffS1" cert="medium">Lady Raffles</persName> on Friday<lb/>
                    morning - return same day -<lb/>
                    Tea at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DenmA1" cert="medium">Lady Dinman's</persName>Lady Dinman's on<lb/>
                    Saturday to meet my Lord whom<lb/>
                    I much like or admire - else I<lb/>
                    would not stir a foot for him and<lb/>
                    would rather take tea at home<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    Sunday to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GrifF1" cert="medium">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi> . Griffths</persName> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">Lestocks</persName><lb/>
                    friend - and the friend of Order<lb/>
                    wrote the <unclear>mel</unclear><hi rend="superscript">g</hi> . regulation book you know<lb/>
                    or if you don't <unclear>vide</unclear> <unclear>Hall closet</unclear><lb/>
                    if you care to know -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    He has been very kind to me &amp; I know that<lb/>
                    15. <add>Instant</add> Monday - I believe I shall dine<lb/>
                    for the last time - with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt B</persName><lb/>
                    and see the baby &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtS1">Sophy</persName> whom<lb/>
                    we have never yet seen -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    They have very judiciously kept,<lb/>
                    her perfectly quiet - Oh how wish<lb/>
                    but malheur passé - &amp;c -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I cannot yet positively say on which<lb/>
                    day tuesday wednesday thursday<lb/>
                    we go to the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoilX1">Moillets</persName> but will<lb/>
                    write again when quite near my<lb/>
                    projection<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    Mean time Dearest<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> your poor poor little pencil<lb/>
                    commission shall be cared for<lb/>
                    and is that all! you can think of<lb/>
                    for me to do for you my dearest<lb/>
                    madam -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I do not know when <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3"><choice> <orig>FME</orig><reg>Frances Maria Edgeworth</reg></choice></persName><lb/>
                    wrote to you last or whether she told<lb/>
                    you our history up to the day we<lb/>
                    came here - But for fear of missing<lb/>
                    so important an event I must (go to page<lb/>
                    second<lb/></p>
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
